== SUSY QM superalgebra ==

In fundamental quantum mechanics, we learn that an algebra of operators is defined by commutation relations among those operators. For example, the canonical operators of position and momentum have the commutator formula_34. (Here, we use &quot;natural units&quot; where the Planck constant is set equal to 1.) A more intricate case is the algebra of angular momentum operators; these quantities are closely connected to the rotational symmetries of three-dimensional space. To generalize this concept, we define an &quot;anticommutator&quot;, which relates operators the same way as an ordinary commutator, but with the opposite sign:
: formula_35

If operators are related by anticommutators as well as commutators, we say they are part of a &quot;Lie superalgebra&quot;. Let&#x27;s say we have a quantum system described by a Hamiltonian formula_36 and a set of formula_37 operators formula_38. We shall call this system &quot;supersymmetric&quot; if the following anticommutation relation is valid for all formula_39:
: formula_40

If this is the case, then we call &quot;formula_38&quot; the system&#x27;s &quot;supercharges&quot;.

